05173nam a22007575i 9780231541343DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016013380  a97802315413437 a10.7312/harr177722doi  a(DE-B1597)479840  a(OCoLC)979575424  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPS228.M63bH37 2016 4aPS228.M63bH37 2016 7aLIT0040202bisacsh04a810.9/1122231 aHarris, Donal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn Company Time :bAmerican Modernism in the Big Magazines /cDonal Harris. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b11 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aModernist Latitudes00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Making Modernism Big -- t1. Willa Cather’s Promiscuous Fiction -- t2. Printing the Color Line in The Crisis -- t3. On the Clock: Rewriting Literary Work at Time Inc. -- t4. Our Eliot: Mass Modernism and the American Century -- t5. Hemingway’s Disappearing Style -- tAfterword: Working from Home -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerican novelists and poets who came of age in the early twentieth century were taught to avoid journalism "like wet sox and gin before breakfast." It dulled creativity, rewarded sensationalist content, and stole time from "serious" writing. Yet Willa Cather, W. E. B. Du Bois, Jessie Fauset, James Agee, T. S. Eliot, and Ernest Hemingway all worked in the editorial offices of groundbreaking popular magazines and helped to invent the house styles that defined McClure's, The Crisis, Time, Life, Esquire, and others. On Company Time tells the story of American modernism from inside the offices and on the pages of the most successful and stylish magazines of the twentieth century. Working across the borders of media history, the sociology of literature, print culture, and literary studies, Donal Harris draws out the profound institutional, economic, and aesthetic affiliations between modernism and American magazine culture. Starting in the 1890s, a growing number of writers found steady paychecks and regular publishing opportunities as editors and reporters at big magazines. Often privileging innovative style over late-breaking content, these magazines prized novelists and poets for their innovation and attention to literary craft. In recounting this history, On Company Time challenges the narrative of decline that often accompanies modernism's incorporation into midcentury middlebrow culture. Its integrated account of literary and journalistic form shows American modernism evolving within as opposed to against mass print culture. Harris's work also provides an understanding of modernism that extends beyond narratives centered on little magazines and other "institutions of modernism" that served narrow audiences. And for the writers, the "double life" of working for these magazines shaped modernism's literary form and created new models of authorship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAuthors and publisherszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 0aPeriodicalsxPublishingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular literaturezUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857840uhttps://doi.org/10.7